This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) because it focuses on learning multimodal representations for discriminative tasks such as sentiment prediction. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of natural language processing techniques for some of the datasets used in the experiments. 

The paper is also likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) because it deals with learning representations from visual and textual modalities. 

Furthermore, the paper could belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) because it proposes a model that optimizes for a joint generative-discriminative objective across multimodal data and labels. 

The paper could also belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) because it deals with learning representations from multiple sources of information, which is a fundamental problem in AI. 

Lastly, the paper could belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.MM (Multimedia) because it deals with learning representations from multiple modalities, including visual, textual, and acoustic.
